<DOC><DOCNO> AP880517-0194 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-05-17-88 2038EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-Guatemala     05-17 0402</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Guatemala,0412</SECOND><HEAD>Ex-Presidential Candidates Involved in Coup Attempt, PresidentSays</HEAD><BYLINE>By ALFONSO ANZUETO</BYLINE><BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE><DATELINE>GUATEMALA CITY (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   President Vinicio Cerezo said Tuesday thattwo former presidential candidates were among the civiliansinvolved in last week's failed coup attempt against his government.   He identified them as Gustavo Anzueto Vielman, the candidate in1982 for the ultraconservative Authentic Nationalist Center party,and Mario David Garcia, the party's candidate in 1985 and directorof a television news program.   The army has said eight civilians were involved in lastWednesday's attempt. Six army officers, including deputy commandersof two bases, are under arrest and three others were retiredtemporarily or permanently.   The president identified another purported plotter as MarioCastejon, who was a member of the National Renovation Party and wastrying to form his own party. For a time Castejon was with theU.S.-backed Contra rebels fighting to overthrow Nicaragua's leftistSandinista government.   Cerezo, who took office on Jan. 14, 1986 as Guatemala's firstcivilian president since 1970, said military authorities will filecomplaints in civilian courts against the civilians involved. Nonewas under arrest Tuesday.   He spoke with reporters after inaugurating a preventivedetention center at the Pavon prison in Fraijanes, 15 miles east ofthe capital.   Cerezo said the former military officers involved in the coupattempt included retired Gen. Mario Lopez Fuentes, military chiefof staff during the government of Gen. Efrain Rios Montt and untilrecently Guatemalan ambassador to Italy, and retired Col. FernandoLuis Gordillo Martinez, who was a member of the junta formed afterthe March 23, 1982 coup that brought Rios Montt to power.   The junta later was dissolved and Rios Montt named president.   Gordillo Martinez is secretary-general of the Emergent ConcordMovement, a small political party. His brother, Maj. Manuel MariaGordillo Martinez, who was in charge of training at the base inRetalhuleu, is among the active officers under arrest in theattempt.   Columns of officers and soldiers from the bases at Retalhuleu,115 miles southwest of Guatemala City, and Jutiapa, 75 milessoutheast, were stopped by troops loyal to the government as therebel soldiers moved toward the capital early Wednesday.   Officials said the forces were stopped peacefully.   Rios Montt was overthrown in an Aug. 8, 1983, coup and replacedby Gen. Humberto Mejia Victores, who in 1986 turned over thegovernment to Cerezo, the winner in two rounds of elections.</TEXT></DOC>